4
00:00:12.700 --> 00:00:16.545
I don't see any hands up, but that's good.

5
00:00:16.545 --> 00:00:19.365
Because if there were experts in the audience,

6
00:00:19.365 --> 00:00:24.035
I would wonder why you are wasting your time on a Coursera class.

7
00:00:24.035 --> 00:00:28.725
In course one of our specialization on embedding sensors and actuators,

8
00:00:28.725 --> 00:00:31.750
we will take a deep dive into temperature sensors.

9
00:00:31.750 --> 00:00:34.025
The granddaddy of all sensors.

10
00:00:34.025 --> 00:00:37.134
Its history dates back to the 18th century

11
00:00:37.134 --> 00:00:40.555
when guys named Fahrenheit and Celsius were around.

12
00:00:40.555 --> 00:00:45.385
We will get you started with your piece of development kit both hardware and software.

13
00:00:45.385 --> 00:00:48.150
There will be a few labs for you to do on schematics,

14
00:00:48.150 --> 00:00:51.725
amplifiers, wiring, and adding sensors to the kit.

15
00:00:51.725 --> 00:00:53.965
Then, we'll explain rotary sensors.

16
00:00:53.965 --> 00:00:56.555
You'll do some lab work with those sensors.

17
00:00:56.555 --> 00:00:59.625
Last, will tackle amplifiers,

18
00:00:59.625 --> 00:01:02.695
circuit diagrams, derivation of grade equations,

19
00:01:02.695 --> 00:01:04.615
noise issues and spec sheets.

20
00:01:04.615 --> 00:01:08.995
You need expertise on amplifiers to work with sensors because there's

21
00:01:08.995 --> 00:01:13.620
no such thing as a sensor circuit that doesn't have an amplifier.

22
00:01:13.620 --> 00:01:17.400
My partner Jim and I believe that online education should be just as

23
